[2] Spread and emergence
Date: Tue 24 Sep 2019
Source: Journal of Medical Entomology [edited]
https://academic.oup.com/jme/advance-article/doi/10.1093/jme/tjz151/5572102


ref: Kramer LD, Ciota AT, Kilpatrick AM. Introduction, spread, and establishment of West Nile virus in the Americas. J Med Entomol. 2019. pii: tjz151. doi: 10.1093/jme/tjz151. [Epub ahead of print]
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
The introduction of West Nile virus (WNV) to North America in 1999 and its subsequent rapid spread across the Americas demonstrated the potential impact of arboviral introductions to new regions, and this was reinforced by the subsequent introductions of chikungunya and Zika viruses. Extensive studies of host-pathogen-vector-environment interactions over the past two decades have illuminated many aspects of the ecology and evolution of WNV and other arboviruses, including the potential for pathogen adaptation to hosts and vectors, the influence of climate, land use and host immunity on transmission ecology, and the difficulty in preventing the establishment of a zoonotic pathogen with abundant wildlife reservoirs. Here, we focus on outstanding questions concerning the introduction, spread, and establishment of WNV in the Americas, and what it can teach us about the future of arboviral introductions. Key gaps in our knowledge include the following: viral adaptation and coevolution of hosts, vectors and the virus; the mechanisms and species involved in the large-scale spatial spread of WNV; how weather modulates WNV transmission; the drivers of large-scale variation in enzootic transmission; the ecology of WNV transmission in Latin America; and the relative roles of each component of host-virus-vector interactions in spatial and temporal variation in WNV transmission. Integrative studies that examine multiple factors and mechanisms simultaneously are needed to advance our knowledge of mechanisms driving transmission.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[West Nile virus and the disease it causes in some species of birds and in humans has been with us in the USA for 20 years. Historically, after a surprising outbreak of an infectious disease, the lessons learned during the outbreak tend to fade from institutional memory. However, West Nile virus gives us annual reminders. The Kramer et al. article (item [2] above) provides a thoughtful assessment of the introduction of WNV into the USA and its subsequent spread in North America and beyond in the Americas and the responses that followed. She and her colleagues underscore the gaps in our knowledge. The need for interdisciplinary teamwork in these kinds of disease emergence and emergencies is emphasized and should be carried out within the conceptual framework of one health.

Going forward, it will be interesting to see whether there will be continuous support for the public health infrastructure that Dr Kramer mentions. It is difficult to predict when and where the next exotic pathogenic organism will arrive in the USA. It may be one of the viruses, bacteria, or parasites that ProMED-mail monitors in countries outside of the USA. But one will arrive. Will we be ready?

ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka has provided additional references from the Jounal of Medical Entomology that ProMED-mail readers may find of interest:

1. Reisen WK. Twenty years of West Nile virus in the United States: Introduction. J Med Entomol. 2019 Sep 24. pii: tjz130. doi: 10.1093/jme/tjz130. [Epub ahead of print]; https://doi.org/10.1093/jme/tjz130.
2. Bosco-Lauth AM, Bowen RA. West Nile Virus: Veterinary health and vaccine development. Angela M Bosco-Lauth, Richard A Bowen. J Med Entomol. 2019 Sep 24. pii: tjz125. doi: 10.1093/jme/tjz125. [Epub ahead of print]; https://doi.org/10.1093/jme/tjz125.
3. Duggal NK, Langwig KE, Ebel GD, Brault AC. On the fly: interactions between birds, mosquitoes, and environment that have molded West Nile virus genomic structure over two decades. J Med Entomol. 2019 Sep 24. pii: tjz112. doi: 10.1093/jme/tjz112. [Epub ahead of print]; https://doi.org/10.1093/jme/tjz112.
4. Rochlin I, Faraji A, Healy K, Andreadis TG. West Nile virus mosquito vectors in North America. J Med Entomol. 2019. pii: tjz146. doi: 10.1093/jme/tjz146. [Epub ahead of print]; https://doi.org/10.1093/jme/tjz146.
5. Kilpatrick AM, Wheeler SS. Impact of West Nile virus on bird populations: limited lasting effects, evidence for recovery, and gaps in our understanding of impacts on ecosystems. J Med Entomol. 2019 Sep 24. pii: tjz149. doi: 10.1093/jme/tjz149. [Epub ahead of print] https://doi.org/10.1093/jme/tjz149.
6. Nasci RS, Mutebi JP. Reducing West Nile virus risk through vector management. J Med Entomol. 2019 Sep 24. pii: tjz083. doi: 10.1093/jme/tjz083. [Epub ahead of print]; https://doi.org/10.1093/jme/tjz083.
